%N A388424 Number of axis-aligned 2 X 2 squares in the 3D projection of a (3n+2)-dimensional hypercube with side length 2.
%C A388424 This is the case k = 2 of the parametric family A_{3n+2}(k) = k^n*(k^(n+1)-1)^2 + 2*k^(n+1)*(k^(n+1)-1)*(k^n-1), which counts axis-aligned 2 X 2 squares in the 3D (orthogonal) projection of a d-dimensional hypercube with d = 3n+2. Thus a(n) = 2^n*(2^(n+1)-1)^2 + 2*2^(n+1)*(2^(n+1)-1)*(2^n-1) is the number of 2 X 2 tiles in the 3D projection of the 5, 8, 11, ...-dimensional hypercubes (side 2).
%C A388424 We observe that the first term of the sequence for n = 0 is 1, since it represents the only square tile that can be constructed with 2 X 2 points.
%H A388424 Salvatore Ferraro, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.17119797">Counting axis-aligned 2X2 tiles in the 3D projection of hypercubes (short note)</a>, Zenodo, 2025.
%H A388424 <a href="/index/Rec#order_03">Index entries for linear recurrences with constant coefficients</a>, signature (14,-56,64).
%F A388424 a(n) = 12*2^(3*n) - 16*2^(2*n) + 5*2^n.
%F A388424 G.f.: (1+28*x)/((1-2*x)*(1-4*x)*(1-8*x)).
%p A388424 a := n -> 2^n*(2^(n+1)-1)^2 + 2*2^(n+1)*(2^(n+1)-1)*(2^n-1):
%p A388424 seq(a(n), n=0..40);
%t A388424 Table[2^n (2^(n + 1) - 1)^2 + 2*2^(n + 1) (2^(n + 1) - 1) (2^n - 1), {n, 0, 40}]
%o A388424 (Python)
%o A388424 def a(n:int)->int:
%o A388424     return (2**n)*(2**(n+1)-1)**2 + 2*(2**(n+1))*(2**(n+1)-1)*((2**n)-1)
%o A388424 print([a(n) for n in range(40)])
